<Base title="Our Standard — Grimsley Mineral Co." active="standard">
  <div class="pagehead">
    <div class="inner">
      <div class="crumb"><a href={u("")}>Home</a> / Our Standard</div>
      <h1>Our Standard</h1>
      <p>A specimen is only as good as the information that comes with it. We grade and describe every piece the same way, so you always know what you are buying before it ships.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="prose">
    <ol>
      <li><b>Honest about condition.</b>We look each specimen over for chips, bruises, contacts, and repairs, and we say what we find. Natural imperfections are part of collecting, so we point them out plainly instead of hiding them in a good camera angle.</li>
      <li><b>Crystal quality over size.</b>A bigger specimen is not automatically a better one. We choose pieces for luster, color, clarity, and clean crystal form first. Size matters, but it never covers for a dull or damaged crystal.</li>
      <li><b>Documented locality.</b>Where a specimen came from is part of its value and its story. We list the locality as specifically as we can, down to the mine or region when the source is known, and we do not guess or dress it up when it is not.</li>
      <li><b>Honest treatment disclosure.</b>Some material is treated, and that is fine when it is disclosed. If a piece is heat treated, dyed, or stabilized, we say so. Most commercial citrine is heat treated amethyst, and we label it that way.</li>
      <li><b>Accurate photography.</b>Our photos show the specimen as it is, in even light, without filters that punch up color beyond real life. What you see on the screen is what arrives at your door.</li>
    </ol>
  </div>

  <section class="trust" id="field-notes">
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="sec-top"><div class="k">Field Notes</div><h2>Know what you're buying</h2></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="prose">
    <h2>How a specimen earns its grade</h2>
    <p>Grading a mineral is less about a single number and more about reading a piece the way a collector would. We start with the crystal itself. Is the luster bright or dull, is the color even and true to the species, are the crystal faces sharp or worn. A vivid, well formed crystal with strong luster sits at the top, and a cloudy or etched one sits lower even if it is large.</p>
    <p>Next we look at condition. We check the display faces for chips, contacts where the specimen grew against something else, and any repairs or restoration. A repair does not ruin a specimen, but it changes what it is worth, so it has to be disclosed.</p>
    <p>Then we weigh aesthetics. How the crystals are arranged, how the specimen sits, whether it has a clean natural base all factor in. Finally we consider rarity for the locality, since a common mineral from a famous find can still be special. None of this is a formula. It is judgment, applied the same way every time.</p>

    <h2>What a locality tells you</h2>
    <p>When we say a specimen is from Mibladen, Morocco or Novo Horizonte, Brazil, we are not just listing a place. A locality is a fingerprint. Certain mines produce a certain look, a habit and color and crystal style that experienced collectors can recognize on sight.</p>
    <p>Locality tells you what to expect and what to check. Vanadinite from Mibladen tends toward bright red hexagonal crystals. Cobaltoan calcite from the Congo carries that unmistakable pink. Knowing the source helps you judge whether a piece is typical, exceptional, or possibly mislabeled. Vague labels like "Brazil" or "Africa" are a signal to ask more questions.</p>
    <p>We list locality as specifically as the specimen allows. When the exact mine is known, we name it. When it is not, we tell you that too, rather than inventing detail to make a piece sound better than its paperwork supports.</p>

    <h2>What fades and what dissolves</h2>
    <p>Minerals feel permanent, but some are surprisingly fragile once they leave the ground. Light is the first thing to watch. Certain species fade with long sun exposure, including amethyst, celestite, and some fluorite, whose color can weaken over years on a bright windowsill. Keep light sensitive pieces out of direct sun.</p>
    <p>Water and humidity are the next concern. A few minerals are water soluble or absorb moisture from the air, halite and some sulfates among them, and can slowly degrade in a damp room. Pyrite can react with humidity over time and break down. Stable, moderate humidity protects most collections.</p>
    <p>Dust and handling do quiet damage too. Fingertips leave oils, and repeated wiping can scratch soft minerals or dull a delicate luster. Use a soft brush or gentle air rather than a cloth on fragile crystals. Treat a specimen as the record it is, and it will outlast all of us.</p>
  </div>
</Base>
